Topic 2 - Prompt Techniques: Zero-Shot, One-Shot & Few-Shot Prompting Made Practical
Submitted By: Aman Dekate
Introduction
Prompt techniques help users communicate more effectively with AI by providing clear instructions and examples when needed. Choosing the right prompting technique improves the accuracy, consistency, and relevance of AI-generated responses. The three main techniques are Zero-Shot, One-Shot, and Few-Shot Prompting.
Zero-Shot Prompting
Definition: Zero-Shot Prompting asks the AI to perform a task without any examples.

Example: 'Summarize the following paragraph in one sentence.'

Why: The AI relies only on the instruction.

Best Use Cases: Text summarization, translation, grammar correction, and question answering.
One-Shot Prompting
Definition: One-Shot Prompting provides one example before asking the AI to perform a similar task.

Example:
Question: What is AI?
Answer: AI refers to machines that can perform tasks requiring human intelligence.
Now answer: What is Prompt Engineering?

Why: One example guides the expected format.

Best Use Cases: Customer support, email writing, and content generation.
Few-Shot Prompting
Definition: Few-Shot Prompting provides multiple examples so the AI learns a pattern.

Example:
Good morning → Greeting
Thank you → Appreciation
Now classify: Congratulations

Why: Multiple examples improve consistency.

Best Use Cases: Classification, structured responses, and maintaining writing style.
Comparison
Zero-Shot: No examples; best for simple tasks.
One-Shot: One example; best for learning a format.
Few-Shot: Multiple examples; best for pattern recognition and consistency.
Practical Applications
These prompting techniques are used in chatbots, virtual assistants, content writing, customer support, translation, summarization, data classification, and code generation.
Key Learning
• Understood the differences between Zero-Shot, One-Shot, and Few-Shot Prompting.
• Learned when to use each technique.
